Topic-wise, I think it's cool enough, solution wise, it can be better, you've used 4 loops and one extra list which is kinda "too much"!
as a basic solution, I suggest this one :
d = int(input())
n = int(input())
L = list(map(int,input().split()))
c=0
for i in L:
    for k in L:
        if i!=k:
            if k-i<=d:
                c+=1
print(c)

In C#, there is problem with the stub:
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        {
            int i = int.Parse(inputs[i]);
        }

It uses "int i" inside a loop where the counter is "int i"
